nd got them to producing good size vegetable crops and began selling corn, tomatoes and other vegetables during the summer with pumpkins in the fall.    In 1998, after two years of studying and planning, we put in our first acre of strawberries. We fixed up an old tobacco barn and started our strawberry business. We now have strawberries, blackberries, sweet corn and tomatoes. We hope that our customers love coming to our farm \'cause we love being here.    For the last 12 years, we\'ve grown everything from strawberries to haunted corn. We\'ve tried just about everything to know what works for us and what doesn\'t. Alot has changed for us over the years, personally and professionally. We no longer have the weekend textile job that we enjoyed that allowed us to \"farm\" during the week. And we no longer have the haunted corn \"maze\". What we do have is the desire to keep farming, a growing family, and a full-time job(for one of us at least). In 2009, for personal reasons, we decided not to have our strawberry patch open. We had to take time to prioritize our life and focus on family. We will not have the strawberries again in 2010. However, we WILL have them in Spring, 2011. For 2010, we will have U-pick/We-pick blackberries, sweet corn and tomatoes. ','336-421-0693 ','hallsberries@bellsouth.net ','Thomas & Tina Hall','','Blackberries-July thru August/Monday thru Saturday 8AM to 7PM, Strawberries(2011)-mid-April thru mid June/Monday thru Saturday 8AM to 7PM ','','','','179 Oakus Page Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','27320 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:26','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7cd9bcb5-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Matkins Meats, Inc.','Matkins Meat, Inc. was founded in 1956 by Leonard Matkins and Associates. His son Jerry, has been running the business for 40+ years. Matkins Meats, Processors, Inc. proudly celebrated our 50 year anniversary in 2006.   Matkins Meats is a slaughter and processing facility. Cows, Pigs, Sheep, Goat, Buffalo, Beefalo, Water Buffalo, Ostrich, Emu, & Deer are our specialty...   We accept animals for slaughtering Monday - Thursday 8 am - 3 pm, no appointment needed but call first please..   Our sausages include: Mild / Mild Extra Sage, Hot / Hot Extra Sage, Sweet / Hot / Zesty Italian, Bratz / Garlic Bratz, Chorizo, Maple, Kielbasa & Anduille Links are charged according to the quantity used.   In addition to slaughtering & processing, another department is the production of Matkins Chili. It is one of a kind. It\'s great heated by itself, on hot dogs, as spagetti meat sauce, on tacos, or with beans in it. It is so meaty....you\'re gonna love it...!!! (See our recipes!!) ','336-584-8247 ','matkinsmeats@bellsouth.net','Jerry Matkins','','7 am - 3:30 pm Closed all holidays that the Post Office is closed. ','','','','9683 Kerr Chapel Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','27249 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:26','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7cdae926-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Raynay Alpaca Farm LLC','We are located in Caswell County and have recently brought our alpacas to our newly renovated home on Ashland Road. We currently have 8 alpacas in our herd, 4 huacaya and 4 suri. Three of our girls are expecting crias (babies) in the Spring/Summer of \'10.  Our goal is to educate the public about alpacas and all the wonderful attributes of their fiber which will be displayed in our gift shop as yarn and finished handmade alpaca hats, scarves, ponchos, shawls and vests.   Please call and make an appointment to take a farm tour and visit our herd up close. ','336 939-9400 ','mgbcandy@aol.com ','Candy McMahan','','Monday-Saturday 10-4 by appointment only at this time.','','www.raynayalpacas.com ','','1897 Ashland Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','27326 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:26','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7cdc48c2-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Sleepy Goat Farm  ','Jon Dorman and Della Williams are both board-certified neurologists who found themselves contemplating a career change. Since they had had goats on a small scale for many years, it was natural that they thought about doing something with the goats. The farm was, until 1989, a working tobacco farm. Della and Jon bought it in that year and stopped the growing of tobacco on the farm. It was that year that they bought Ethel, their first goat.Goat cheese was the next step. The goats had been kept as pets; caretakers and family drank the fresh milk and made cheese and soap until 2003 when the commercial cheese scheme started taking structure.   After 10 years of medical practice without farming, they purchased two goats from Redtail Ridge in Bonny Doon California. The first year of making cheese was hard work but rewarding. The kinds of cheese were limited to a fresh one (chevre) and a surface-mold-ripened (Boucheron) one with a few pounds of feta and 3 large \'Tomme\'. At that point, it was unclear if it were success or a€?the inability to get out of it\' which prompted the preparation for the second season (2005) of making goat cheese. Meeting people who buy goat cheese was a wonderful experience for both Jon and Della. They have made many new acquaintances in the process.    Each day, 1-4 people (depending on who is available) feed, water, milk, make & package cheese, and clean the barn. The bucks are kept in another field and the doelings in still another field until mating season is over; then they join the adult females. (Doelings aren\'t mated until their second year by design). The does are mated in the fall and start delivering about January. From January until the following fall, THERE IS NO TIME: milking, pasteurizing, feeding and being there generally to help with deliveries keeps everyone busy 14-16 hours a day for at least 2 months a€| longer when the babies straggle into life over a 2 month period. ','1.336.388.5388 ','slpygoat@gamewood.net ','Della Williams','','The farm is open to visitors on the 2nd Sunday of each month, between May and August, from 2-5 PM, SleepyGoat Cheeses may be purchased at local markets, Online sale is being considered, despite cost factors for two-day delivery. ','','www.sleepygoatfarm.com ','','7215 Allison Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','27311 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:26','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7cdd9921-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Sleepy Goat Farm ','Jon Dorman and Della Williams are Neurologists who have owned this 160 acre former tobacco farm for over 20 years. One of our first acquisitions was Ethel, a little Alpine goat kid who became totally attached to Della, and this was the start of our goat saga.   Lucy (Nubian) and Liza (grade goat) were Ethel\'s first playmates, then later came the first Oberhasli dairy goats. Kelly and Bill Krantz managed the farm and goats while Della and Jon practiced in Dubai nine years. When the Krantz\'s moved to Ohio in 2003, we returned to the farm.    Della, a creative cook, was interested in cheese making and we were amazed at how delicious the Oberhasli milk was. After consulting with NCDA to build cheese and milking rooms, we were licensed in 2004. The rest of the story is the developing of many cheese types to market to enthusiastic customers! ','336 388 5388 ','slpygoat@yahoo.com ','Jon Dorman','','Call for arrangements','','www.sleepygoatfarm.com ','','7215 Allison Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','27311 ','','','','2012-