The city was asked for help in determining a location that would be convenient for shoppers and of benefit to the city itself. Permission was granted for the market to use Pecan Park a tiny but beautiful park with huge pecan trees for shade.    We love our park and have weathered the pains of start-up and now with more experience are creating a wonderful atmosphere every Thursday afternoon for the residents of Statesville and surrounding areas to buy locally grown produce and goods, meet friends, and participate in our special events that we sponsor to aquaint our customers with using the goods we produce. ','704-873-3361 ','meggena@att.net ','Madge Eggena','','Thursday Evenings, April through October, 4:00 p.m. - \'till.','','','','123 N. Center ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','28677 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fe0db76-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','The Farm At Weathers Creek  ','This slice of land we call home is located in the eastern notch of Iredell County about 40 minutes north of Charlotte, NC. Of the 63 acres, the largest part of bottom land is currently devoted to hay crops. Our vegetable garden is small but bountiful. We grow what we love to eat and sell freshly picked seasonal crops each Saturday at the Davidson Farmers Market. We use sustainable methods only, no chemical fertilizers or pesticides.     In August, 2009 we began hosting The Weathers Creek Writers\' Series, an opportunity for writers of all levels to learn in a small workshop setting. Coming in the summer of 2010 - more writers and artists heading this way. ','704-450-5500 ','weatherscreek@aol.com ','Susan Campbell','','By appointment only. ','','www.weatherscreek.net/ ','','1170 Shinnville Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','27013 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fe25dcc-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','VanHoy Farms Family Campground  ','VanHoy Farms Family Campground offers over 100 rolling peaceful acres of land with full camping facilities and amenities. Sites are grassy with shady trees nearby. Go for a hike or wade through our stream. Listen to music on the deck by the pool in the summer or attend one of the many special events at our coliseum. A nearby Amish village offers breads, candies and fresh produce. We\'re also close to apple and peach orchards. Come see why everything\'s better...\"down on the farm\"!     Quick Facts * Convenient location in UnionGrove, North Carolina in Iredell County * 34 Full hookups * 60 Pull-through sites, 65 ft * 85 Water and electric sites * 2 Cabins with air and heat * Dumping stations * Special sites for primitive campers * Modern bathhouse featuring clean restrooms and hot showers * Amenities include hiking trail, pool, indoor and outdoor arenas with concerts and events year-round * Open year-round * Good Sam park and members of the NC Campground Owners Assocation * Discounts for most major organizations.     Visit our website at www.vanhoyfarms.com for information regarding past and present events at VanHoy Farms. Check and see if you would agree with what our Grandfather always said. The late great H.P. VanHoy, founder of the Ole Time Fiddlers Convention, said that we are the \"Hub of the Universe.\" We like to think so and want you to join us down on the farm and make it your hub as well. We hope that you will find the peace and tranquility that we expereince and others tell us about. We extend this invitation to you today and always. ','704-539-5493 ','cwvh@yadtel.net ','Casey and Phyllis VanHoy','','Year-round: 9:00 a.m. - 10:00 p.m.','','www.vanhoyfarms.com ','','742 Jericho Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','28634 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fe34964-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Yellow Wolf Farm','We are a small farm located in the foothills of NC. We raise grass fed, antibiotic/hormone free meats, AGS Nigerian Miniature Dairy Goats, pasture raised, Heritage poultry and sheep and farm fresh produce. Our animals are humanely raised and our produce is grown organically. We rely on the animals for compost/fertilizer and the chickens do a great job of controlling pests!     We also make pottery with Mud Puppies Studio. Pottery, original paintings and crafts are for sell at the Ashe farmer\'s Market and on Ebay under user name YELLOWWOLFFARM. ','336-709-6541 ','yellowwolffarm@yahoo.com ','Stacy Martin','','By appoinment only. ','','www.yellowwolffarm.com ','','375 Reavis Rd ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','28634 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fe49456-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Catamount Honey  ','Catamount Honey is a small family owned and operated bee business which sales Pure Wildflower and Sourwood Honey wholesale to Western North Carolina retail stores and at local festivals in WNC.    We bottle Pure Wildflower Honey year round which is all natural raw filtered unpasturized honey. Our table honey gives you the old timey real honey taste and flavors honey lovers want with the health benefits of spring pollen.   Our Summer Sourwood Honey, made by our bees and the local beekeepers that we buy from is sweet, light in color and so good, but only available in the Fall.   We also carry the very popular Tupelo Honey from the Florida Panhandle area.','828-349-9045 ','al.mcneely@gmail.com ','Al McNeely','','Daily Mon-Sat 9:00 AM to 6:00 PM by phone, Closed every Sunday and National Holidays, For local pickup call first please. ','','','','P.O. Box 2530 ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','28723 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fe5f6d5-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Ty-Lyn Plantation, LLC  ','Enjoy hot cider while picking out and cutting your own tree. We have trees that range from 3-18 feet in height. From all four major roads into Cashiers, follow the Santa signs to get to our plantation. While having your tree bailed to carry home, visit our wreath operation - all hand made to take with you. We sell wreaths, garland, table decorations and ornaments. Here at Ty-Lyn we have made award-winning wreaths for over 13 years. We have presented the Governor of North Carolina with a wreath for his home in Raleigh, NC and won the Grand Champion Wreath in the North Carolina State Fair Contest with entries from all over the state. Come visit us and stay the day, make it a family tradition to pick and cut your own tree from our fields. Enjoy food for sale on the major weekends. Playground and restrooms available. Take a ride in our hydrogen assisted eco-friendly 1950 Chevy Truck or 1951 Ford Fire Truck and have fun. The kids, and grown-ups, will love it! ','8287433899','tylynplantation@verizon.net','Joni Wavra','','November 21-December 20 Monday-Friday 1-5 pm Saturday & Sunday and the Friday after Thanksgiving 9-5','','tylynplantation.com ','','971 Lloyd Hooper Road ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','28723 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fe7acde-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Appalachian Homestead Farm & Preserve  ','Appalachian Homestead Farm & Preserve is a historic hardscrabble farm established as a nonprofit 501(c)3 tax-exempt organization focused on education, advocacy and research. We have in our possession the original land grant documents dating to 1834 and 1856 when white settlers first came to the far western mountains of NC. Just as settlers found it necessary to work together across the steep mountain terrain to raise barns and cabins, clear newground, make quilts and molasses (and sometimes moonshine!), and to bury the dead and shepherd new babies into this little corner of God\'s world, Appalachian Homestead Farm & Preserve has found many wonderful community partners, including Catch the Spirit of Appalachia--our primary nonprofit partner, Western Carolina University, Jackson County 4-H, and North Carolina\'s many fine departments of agriculture and farming.    Over the years this 225 acre farmstead was divided and fell out of the Bennett family\'s hands, with the exception of about 15 acres. In 2005, a 52 acre parcel was purchased with a private foundation grant, and an additional 14 acre parcel was purchased in 2007 through private efforts with plans to add it to the nonprofit preserve. This historic farmstead has the original chimneys to the settlers cabins and part of the chestnut log barn still intact. Conservation easements with the Land Trust for the Little Tennessee ensure that the Farm will never be developed and that the headwater streams and plant and animal habitat will be protected in perpetuity. A recent biological survey counts 460 different plant species on the Farm and headwater streams measure at an unheard of 1.047 turbidity (purity) rating.      Currently the Farm is cleaning up 50+ years of neglect and making critical repairs to existing structures through volunteer and service-learning assistance from local citizens and student groups from Western Carolina University. Summer youth camp programs for the past three summers have provided rare opportunities for area youth to participate in heritage, culture and outdoor education programs. Long range plans for the Farm include:   * A living history farm, complete with replica cabins, outbuildings and methods of farming.   * A field farm school to help mountain families learn how to grow small-scale heirloom fruits, vegetables, herbs and native landscape plants as a means of increasing their capacity to hold onto their farmsteads in a rapidly developing region.   *A folk school with affordable and readily accessible workshops where mountain families and youth can learn the traditional craft and culture trade with which they can generate income in the new agri and heritage tourism economies.    * An expanded summer youth program that includes overnight camps and offers special programs for children of all ages with special challenges','828-293-1013 ','vguise@verizon.net ','Vera Holland Guise','','The Farm does not yet have staff, though two couples live in residential units on the farm and help with clean-up and improvements, Vera Guise, founding President of the Farm and a direct descendant of the Bennett clan who lived there from the early 1800\'','','www.appalachianhomesteadfarm.org ','','4088 Tilley Creek R d. ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','28723 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fe890ba-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Summersong Farm','','8287433698','info@summersongfarm.com ','Robin Visceglia','','','','summersongfarm.com ','','PO Box 506 ','7f7a92b8-ea4c-11e0-8606-00306701b527','ed336e0f-f48c-11e0-b192-00306701b527','','28717 ','','','','2012-02-29 15:17:31','a1c3e20e-f181-11e0-8a53-00306701b527',1),('7fea09f1-62e8-11e1-b30d-101f74b66417','ff2b0b4d-203c-11e1-8a87-000c29a5c50c','','06a017ae-28cb-11e1-abb7-000c29a5c50c','Tom Sawyer Tree Farm  ','We grow Fraser Fir Christmas trees, for wholesale and for choose & cut. We have over 80 acres on our farm, and we sit on